[SPEAKER_01]: There'll be more information coming later.

577
00:50:33,909 --> 00:50:43,994
[SPEAKER_01]: We do anticipate working with the city director of transportation and traffic as well as the peer reviewer for traffic.

578
00:50:45,255 --> 00:50:50,158
[SPEAKER_01]: I know there was mention made of the original traffic study.

579
00:50:50,878 --> 00:50:55,021
[SPEAKER_01]: that was completed in 2020.

580
00:50:56,782 --> 00:51:12,492
[SPEAKER_01]: Since we're updating that study with all new traffic counts, all new background development assumptions, new trip generation, it doesn't really make a lot of sense to go over that study because a lot of the conclusions

581
00:51:13,473 --> 00:51:19,439
[SPEAKER_01]: are not relevant given it's three, four years later.

582
00:51:21,321 --> 00:51:27,967
[SPEAKER_01]: Instead, what I'd like to do is just go through an overview of what we're planning to update.

583
00:51:27,987 --> 00:51:35,514
[SPEAKER_01]: I've referenced the director of the Traffic and Transportation Department for Medford.

584
00:51:37,685 --> 00:51:57,113
[SPEAKER_01]: We met with him early in the process, and he had mapped out these locations shown in this graphic, 14 intersections in total, stretching from Riverside Avenue intersection with Felsway, including the site driveway, Myrtle Street.

585
00:51:58,398 --> 00:52:09,701
[SPEAKER_01]: Central Avenue intersections with Felsway, a number of intersections with Central Avenue, a number of intersections with Spring Street, all the way down to Riverside.

586
00:52:10,621 --> 00:52:13,042
[SPEAKER_01]: And this is a fairly extensive study area.

587
00:52:13,162 --> 00:52:16,223
[SPEAKER_01]: And as you can see, it focuses on neighborhood locations.

588
00:52:17,183 --> 00:52:24,185
[SPEAKER_01]: We're going to be doing traffic counts at these locations to get a new picture of the traffic flow and operations.

589
00:52:25,365 --> 00:52:36,590
[SPEAKER_01]: We're also going to be performing a safety review, looking at motor vehicle crash data, site distances, transit services in the area.

590
00:52:37,531 --> 00:52:40,532
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll also look at data from the U.S.

591
00:52:40,592 --> 00:52:46,955
[SPEAKER_01]: Census to get an idea of where residents in this area of Medford work.

592
00:52:47,635 --> 00:52:50,297
[SPEAKER_01]: and what modes of transportation they use.

593
00:52:51,097 --> 00:53:02,864
[SPEAKER_01]: I know there was some discussion in the November 30th meeting about the way the attention paid to transit was a little light.

594
00:53:02,884 --> 00:53:10,349
[SPEAKER_01]: There's a lot more information that's available now, so we can adopt that and incorporate it into the updated study.

595
00:53:11,971 --> 00:53:20,862
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll develop estimates of project trip generation for daily and peak hour time periods, since that's the protocol for traffic studies.

596
00:53:21,883 --> 00:53:27,329
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll do level of service analysis for existing future no build.

597
00:53:28,010 --> 00:53:29,571
[SPEAKER_01]: and future build conditions.

598
00:53:30,471 --> 00:53:40,615
[SPEAKER_01]: Those future conditions will allow us to incorporate projects such as the Encore Casino development or expansion, which was referenced on November 30th.

599
00:53:40,655 --> 00:53:56,841
[SPEAKER_01]: We've been in contact with the city planning staff trying to get traffic information on that project and other developments as well that we should include if they're expected to affect traffic volumes in the study area.

600
00:53:58,001 --> 00:54:07,063
[SPEAKER_01]: Additional points of study include neighborhood considerations, looking at pedestrian facilities, parking conditions, curb use regulations.

601
00:54:09,003 --> 00:54:15,165
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll eventually be looking at potential improvements to mitigate the project's impact.

602
00:54:16,025 --> 00:54:26,367
[SPEAKER_01]: That's one of the last steps that we have in the process and one step that we look at once we know what the impacts are.

603
00:54:28,082 --> 00:54:31,265
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll also look at parking, both in terms of demand and supply.

604
00:54:31,445 --> 00:54:34,949
[SPEAKER_01]: We anticipate the parking to be contained on site.

605
00:54:36,758 --> 00:54:43,942
[SPEAKER_01]: We heard loud and clear the concerns of the neighbors, particularly with regard to traffic and parking on Myrtle street.

606
00:54:44,142 --> 00:54:46,923
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's 1 area we'll be paying close attention to.

607
00:54:48,364 --> 00:54:53,566
[SPEAKER_01]: We think that the way the site is proposed to be laid out, the circulation.

608
00:54:54,327 --> 00:55:00,790
[SPEAKER_01]: Will minimize the use of Myrtle street by project residents and Pat, I don't know if you can go to the.

609
00:55:01,570 --> 00:55:06,415
[SPEAKER_01]: The next slide, which shows the existing site circulation.

610
00:55:07,857 --> 00:55:23,032
[SPEAKER_01]: And you can see that the existing site, as a number of parking spaces, has access to the Fells Way, to the intersection of Amaranth Ave and Myrtle Streets and Lawrence.

611
00:55:23,953 --> 00:55:35,844
[SPEAKER_01]: as well as a driveway coming in from the site, making that intersection a 6-way or a 6-leg intersection.

612
00:55:36,304 --> 00:55:41,048
[SPEAKER_01]: There's also access to the site through the southern end of Amaranth.

613
00:55:41,989 --> 00:56:07,547
[SPEAKER_01]: And we think that the way the existing site is laid out, it sort of lends itself to a splitting up of the traffic, the traffic flow and circulation both from larger trucks that may be accessing the site, as well as smaller vehicles and smaller trucks going to the storage side of the business.

614
00:56:08,468 --> 00:56:27,399
[SPEAKER_01]: The next slide shows proposed site circulation, and you can see that the curb cut to the Felsway is retained, but the curb cut to the Myrtle Street and Amaranth Ave intersection has been closed or discontinued.

615
00:56:28,579 --> 00:56:33,122
[SPEAKER_01]: There is access that's proposed to the garage through Amaranth Ave.

616
00:56:33,462 --> 00:56:50,489
[SPEAKER_01]: to the south end, similar to what's there now, but we feel that the way the site is laid out with the access to the garage available right off of Felsway, pretty much, and the proximity of the parking or the way the parking is,

617
00:56:51,269 --> 00:57:00,952
[SPEAKER_01]: is situated around the site, including the potential for shared parking along the portion of the site that's expected to remain.

618
00:57:01,612 --> 00:57:10,014
[SPEAKER_01]: We think that this is going to serve to really increase the use of the Felsway curb cut and minimize the use of

619
00:57:10,814 --> 00:57:11,874
[SPEAKER_01]: of Myrtle Street.

620
00:57:13,235 --> 00:57:20,977
[SPEAKER_01]: Obviously, there's likely to be some traffic that will use Myrtle Street and use some of the other streets in the neighborhood.

621
00:57:22,738 --> 00:57:27,159
[SPEAKER_01]: But, you know, we think that the majority of it will be on Fellsway.

622
00:57:27,719 --> 00:57:40,183
[SPEAKER_01]: And again, I would expect that a lot of the mitigation that we would be looking at would be ways to address any neighborhood impacts from the project.

623
00:57:41,443 --> 00:57:49,609
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's sort of a 50,000 foot view of where we stand with the update to the traffic study.

624
00:57:49,729 --> 00:57:54,373
[SPEAKER_01]: I think counts were being done this week.

625
00:57:54,973 --> 00:58:07,723
[SPEAKER_01]: So as Pat mentioned, we should have that information incorporated into the study and turned around towards the end of the month and ready for review with the peer reviewer and with the city staff.

626
00:58:09,764 --> 00:58:10,745
[SPEAKER_01]: I'll turn it back over to you, Pat.

627
00:58:16,635 --> 00:58:17,355
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

628
00:58:18,056 --> 00:58:20,898
[SPEAKER_12]: So we just need to.

629
00:58:21,178 --> 00:58:21,698
[SPEAKER_12]: Thanks, Scott.

630
00:58:21,778 --> 00:58:45,974
[SPEAKER_12]: So I think just before moving on to discuss next steps, we wanted to pause and just, I think, take questions and comments related to Scott's presentation or anything that I may have said earlier, but just giving the opportunity to have questions or comments come in there.

631
00:58:47,604 --> 00:58:48,265
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, thank you.

632
00:58:49,385 --> 00:58:53,569
[SPEAKER_10]: So I'd love to hear any questions we have from the board.

633
00:58:54,009 --> 00:59:00,734
[SPEAKER_10]: We are going to have a chance to come back to traffic in a future session.

634
00:59:00,794 --> 00:59:03,977
[SPEAKER_10]: So we'll have a dedicated session that includes

635
00:59:05,353 --> 00:59:08,896
[SPEAKER_10]: more details on the traffic study, some of the peer review feedback.

636
00:59:09,396 --> 00:59:14,681
[SPEAKER_10]: That will be the session where we take public comment on the traffic as well.

637
00:59:15,842 --> 00:59:19,865
[SPEAKER_10]: We already got some high level comments in our kickoff meeting.

638
00:59:20,565 --> 00:59:30,854
[SPEAKER_10]: So yeah, if there's questions from members of the board or things that you're hoping to see in that future hearing, now would be a great time to ask.

639
00:59:42,936 --> 00:59:47,683
[SPEAKER_10]: Not immediately seeing indication from any member of the board.

640
00:59:48,204 --> 00:59:50,568
[SPEAKER_10]: I see a hand from a member of the public.

641
00:59:51,048 --> 00:59:52,791
[SPEAKER_26]: Actually, Mike, sorry for jumping in late.

642
00:59:52,871 --> 00:59:54,574
[SPEAKER_26]: I just... Go ahead, Andre.

643
00:59:56,011 --> 01:00:17,903
[SPEAKER_26]: One thing that I'd love to see in any kind of a traffic study would be looking at connections to transit centers, and in particular, looking at micromobility, looking at shared car spaces and usage, bikes, things like that.

644
01:00:18,283 --> 01:00:23,806
[SPEAKER_26]: So for me, it's not just about vehicular traffic, but all the other things that we might be able to do.

645
01:00:27,102 --> 01:00:28,545
[SPEAKER_06]: All right, thank you, Andre.

646
01:00:29,487 --> 01:00:31,452
[SPEAKER_06]: Other questions from members of the board?

647
01:00:38,442 --> 01:00:42,024
[SPEAKER_10]: All right, well, what I was starting to say, so I do see a hand from a member of the public.

648
01:00:43,084 --> 01:00:44,125
[SPEAKER_10]: I just want to clarify.

649
01:00:44,205 --> 01:00:51,208
[SPEAKER_10]: So 40B hearings tend to be long processes with multiple sessions.

650
01:00:51,848 --> 01:00:54,009
[SPEAKER_10]: There's going to be multiple sessions of this hearing.

651
01:00:54,930 --> 01:00:59,192
[SPEAKER_10]: In this particular meeting, the intention was to provide a brief update.

652
01:01:00,072 --> 01:01:02,614
[SPEAKER_10]: And so we're not taking public comment today.

653
01:01:04,115 --> 01:01:15,243
[SPEAKER_10]: However, the board is going to be discussing with the applicant tonight, and we'll be working with them offline to set the schedule and topics for the remainder of the hearing.

654
01:01:15,323 --> 01:01:21,047
[SPEAKER_10]: And so we do intend to discuss all aspects of the project, including traffic,

655
01:01:22,357 --> 01:01:29,162
[SPEAKER_10]: in future sessions of the hearing, which will be made available in the folder on the ZBA website.

656
01:01:29,282 --> 01:01:36,967
[SPEAKER_10]: So I just wanted to clarify, we're not taking public comment tonight because we're not really going deep into anything tonight.

657
01:01:38,788 --> 01:01:45,672
[SPEAKER_10]: All right, I just wanna say, so I think this was addressed a little bit in Scott's update.

658
01:01:48,834 --> 01:01:51,696
[SPEAKER_10]: I hear the concerns that were raised

659
01:01:52,402 --> 01:01:57,664
[SPEAKER_10]: Thus far, and I think we're included in one of the original department headletters surrounding the traffic flow.

660
01:01:58,164 --> 01:02:05,847
[SPEAKER_10]: So Scott spoke to how the proposal aims to address that.

661
01:02:06,527 --> 01:02:13,950
[SPEAKER_10]: That's an area that I definitely am going to want to get deep into at the appropriate time in the hearing, because I do think if

662
01:02:15,007 --> 01:02:28,516
[SPEAKER_10]: If there's too much traffic flow into some of the adjacent one-way streets, especially with the street parking on the side and so on, it could cause some transportation issues.

663
01:02:28,556 --> 01:02:32,098
[SPEAKER_10]: So I know we're going to be speaking to that, but I just want to call that out up front.

664
01:02:32,138 --> 01:02:35,620
[SPEAKER_10]: I intend for us to zoom in on that aspect especially.

665
01:02:39,863 --> 01:02:43,145
[SPEAKER_07]: Other questions or comments from the board?

666
01:02:50,623 --> 01:02:53,664
[SPEAKER_10]: All right, so thank you both.

667
01:02:54,184 --> 01:02:55,384
[SPEAKER_10]: Appreciate the update.

668
01:02:55,444 --> 01:02:59,005
[SPEAKER_10]: And so next, we're turning it over to Attorney Tam, is that correct?

669
01:03:00,706 --> 01:03:05,487
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes, turning it over to Attorney Tam to discuss proposed next steps.

670
01:03:06,647 --> 01:03:08,868
[SPEAKER_12]: All right, we will unmute you.

671
01:03:09,528 --> 01:03:10,649
[SPEAKER_07]: Please go ahead, Attorney Tam.

672
01:03:11,629 --> 01:03:14,209
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, Mr. Chairman, members of the board.

673
01:03:14,330 --> 01:03:15,830
[SPEAKER_25]: I'll be very brief.

674
01:03:17,300 --> 01:03:40,024
[SPEAKER_25]: I think as Pat alluded to, we're really pleased and appreciative of the coordination by staff to get these peer reviews well underway at this stage and to be able to coordinate and provide for updates to the materials that were originally submitted several years ago in 2020.

675
01:03:42,344 --> 01:03:45,185
[SPEAKER_25]: Wanted to take the opportunity to work with the board

676
01:03:46,114 --> 01:03:58,697
[SPEAKER_25]: on some scheduling so that we can have some reasonable goals to meet and we didn't want to be presumptuous, but we offer up some ideas based on the discussions that have been had to date.

677
01:03:59,917 --> 01:04:12,100
[SPEAKER_25]: I think based upon the discussions between Qube 3 and your consultant Davis Square, we'd expect that those productive discussions that started this week will continue so that

678
01:04:14,689 --> 01:04:38,169
[SPEAKER_25]: We and presumably your consultant at Davis Square can be in a position to provide the board and the public an update on the comments, considerations, and any potential modifications that may be made or may need to be made to the plans that have been shown to you back on November 30th.

679
01:04:38,689 --> 01:04:40,711
[SPEAKER_25]: So we think that that would be an opportune

680
01:04:41,882 --> 01:04:44,523
[SPEAKER_25]: way to use our time on the 30th.

681
01:04:45,804 --> 01:04:56,048
[SPEAKER_25]: And the reason why I'm focused on scheduling a few months out is because obviously there is a statutory time clock that, as you know, has been running.

682
01:04:57,813 --> 01:05:13,785
[SPEAKER_25]: It's no fault of ours and it's no fault of this board's, but that clock is running and by my count, and I can review this with Dennis and Alicia, really that 180 day clock will run through April 1st.

683
01:05:13,825 --> 01:05:21,491
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we're going to be reasonable in terms of what the board may require if additional time is in fact necessary.

684
01:05:22,251 --> 01:05:24,313
[SPEAKER_25]: But we want to at least achieve what we can

685
01:05:25,132 --> 01:05:27,414
[SPEAKER_25]: during that 180-day time period.

686
01:05:29,275 --> 01:05:43,505
[SPEAKER_25]: So if the 30th, and this is at your discretion, if the 30th makes sense to spend some time on design review and to drill down on some of those issues, that seems appropriate to us.

687
01:05:43,825 --> 01:05:54,292
[SPEAKER_25]: If there's time remaining, your civil peer review consultant may be afforded some opportunity

688
01:05:55,074 --> 01:06:05,897
[SPEAKER_25]: provide comment on from the civil side based on what Bowler has previously submitted and what they have proactively will be submitting this week.

689
01:06:07,157 --> 01:06:14,079
[SPEAKER_25]: That essentially will give them two full weeks to at least provide some comments if time permits.

690
01:06:15,979 --> 01:06:22,581
[SPEAKER_25]: And then I understood that you had a subsequent session kind of calendared as we had talked about, I think on the 15th of February.

691
01:06:23,481 --> 01:06:48,671
[SPEAKER_25]: So coming out of Valentine's Day, we might, assuming that Scott completes his updated traffic impact analysis, might be the right time to hear from your consultant at Beta with respect to any outstanding civil issues as well as potentially traffic-related and transportation-related issues.

692
01:06:49,512 --> 01:06:52,753
[SPEAKER_25]: And Mr. Chair, we hear you on both

693
01:06:54,273 --> 01:07:02,021
[SPEAKER_25]: the site circulation as well as the transit concerns that have previously been identified.

694
01:07:02,081 --> 01:07:08,107
[SPEAKER_25]: And I think Pat in his update to you indicates that we're working actively on those issues as well.

695
01:07:10,361 --> 01:07:11,361
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Attorney Tam.

696
01:07:11,561 --> 01:07:12,102
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

697
01:07:12,202 --> 01:07:16,063
[SPEAKER_10]: So a few things to say on these topics.

698
01:07:16,083 --> 01:07:22,826
[SPEAKER_10]: So first of all, we did talk about the opening hearing, the 30th and the 15th.

699
01:07:22,886 --> 01:07:25,987
[SPEAKER_10]: And so it is our intention to proceed with those dates.

700
01:07:27,348 --> 01:07:38,192
[SPEAKER_10]: Cliff Bomer didn't know for certain at that time whether he'd be retained as the architectural peer review consultant, but I believe he did confirm in that meeting his availability for the 30th.

701
01:07:39,798 --> 01:07:45,583
[SPEAKER_10]: I haven't had a chance to check with Beta on their availability for the 15th.

702
01:07:46,204 --> 01:07:49,507
[SPEAKER_10]: Dennis, is that something we've checked with them?

703
01:07:51,348 --> 01:07:54,351
[SPEAKER_20]: They are aware of the dates, and they seem to think that that is fine.

704
01:07:54,371 --> 01:07:55,552
[SPEAKER_20]: They have no issues with that.

705
01:07:56,132 --> 01:07:56,773
[SPEAKER_10]: All right, wonderful.

706
01:07:57,133 --> 01:08:06,962
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, so my intention is to split this up topically, and so to the point of

707
01:08:07,996 --> 01:08:11,858
[SPEAKER_10]: If we have a hearing, should we move on to the next topic?

708
01:08:12,479 --> 01:08:20,963
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm inclined to avoid that, at least in the earlier stages of this hearing, just so that members of the public know the appropriate meeting to tune into.

709
01:08:21,764 --> 01:08:28,067
[SPEAKER_10]: We could do shorter updates on other areas as long as we're not doing the focal presentation for that topic.

710
01:08:30,237 --> 01:08:33,460
[SPEAKER_10]: Design on the 30th sounds great.

711
01:08:34,400 --> 01:08:42,227
[SPEAKER_10]: Sounds civil on the 15th, provided everything's submitted to beta on time.

712
01:08:43,268 --> 01:08:44,108
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's plan on it.

713
01:08:44,729 --> 01:08:52,876
[SPEAKER_10]: And I do think for this hearing, doing traffic as a standalone hearing is worthwhile.

714
01:08:54,617 --> 01:09:02,540
[SPEAKER_10]: So it's my intention to coordinate outside of this meeting on the specific dates for the rest of the hearing.

715
01:09:03,660 --> 01:09:23,648
[SPEAKER_10]: But the sketch you've proposed here, I think the thing that's a little unclear at this point that may cause some changes later in the schedule is just to go through this in the most efficient way possible, we would basically need for each of the three areas, your plans plus the peer review feedback,

716
01:09:24,488 --> 01:09:34,427
[SPEAKER_10]: And maybe even you having already seen that and incorporated it, or maybe we do follow ups, but you know if if we have situations where.

717
01:09:35,455 --> 01:09:38,658
[SPEAKER_10]: we aren't able to parallelize everything.

718
01:09:38,678 --> 01:09:51,151
[SPEAKER_10]: We may have to have follow-ups just to ensure that the applicant has a chance to respond to any peer review feedback that they aren't able to respond to and address in the same meeting.

719
01:09:51,211 --> 01:09:53,834
[SPEAKER_10]: So it's my intention to propose

720
01:09:55,055 --> 01:10:05,580
[SPEAKER_10]: a schedule for the rest of the hearing offline to make sure everyone's available on the required dates for the 30th and the 15th.

721
01:10:06,340 --> 01:10:08,001
[SPEAKER_10]: The dates and topics were locked in.

722
01:10:09,519 --> 01:10:19,466
[SPEAKER_10]: I did see clarification from the city legal counsel as to the statutory timeline.

723
01:10:19,927 --> 01:10:26,091
[SPEAKER_10]: And so my understanding is that we have until May 21st.

724
01:10:27,532 --> 01:10:32,716
[SPEAKER_10]: And so the schedule I put forth will be premised based on that assumption, but

725
01:10:33,352 --> 01:10:41,396
[SPEAKER_10]: Attorney Tam, if you have an alternate legal theory that you want to share with city staff, I'm happy to consider that.

726
01:10:42,617 --> 01:10:49,640
[SPEAKER_10]: As I mentioned in our reopening of the hearing, it's my intention to run a timely and efficient hearing.

727
01:10:49,820 --> 01:10:55,243
[SPEAKER_10]: And so the statutory timeline is just a shared understanding of

728
01:10:56,040 --> 01:11:10,930
[SPEAKER_10]: how long we have if required in the scenario where it seems like up until this point, the applicant has been very motivated and responsive and working with the relevant parties at B to move things along.

729
01:11:11,450 --> 01:11:16,694
[SPEAKER_10]: If that pattern continues, then it's quite possible we will not need the full time.

730
01:11:17,014 --> 01:11:21,977
[SPEAKER_10]: The schedule I put forth is not going to be waiting until the last possible moment.

731
01:11:22,417 --> 01:11:24,639
[SPEAKER_10]: There will be some dates identified

732
01:11:25,837 --> 01:11:35,419
[SPEAKER_10]: through May 21st if needed for, you know, for follow-up sessions for things we don't really have line of sight on today.

733
01:11:36,680 --> 01:11:44,342
[SPEAKER_10]: But yeah, I just wanted to clarify that is my understanding for speaking with City Legal.

734
01:11:44,362 --> 01:11:49,603
[SPEAKER_10]: We have until the 21st of May if so required.

735
01:11:54,019 --> 01:11:57,101
[SPEAKER_25]: And Mr. Chairman, I really appreciate that.

736
01:11:57,141 --> 01:12:04,026
[SPEAKER_25]: And we'll work with you and staff to support that schedule.

737
01:12:05,167 --> 01:12:07,588
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't have an alternate legal theory.

738
01:12:07,668 --> 01:12:08,629
[SPEAKER_25]: I just have math.

739
01:12:09,169 --> 01:12:11,671
[SPEAKER_25]: And the math tells me it's an earlier date.

740
01:12:11,751 --> 01:12:13,692
[SPEAKER_25]: But we won't quibble with it now.

741
01:12:14,713 --> 01:12:20,417
[SPEAKER_25]: We can address that with counsel and with Dennis and Alicia offline.

742
01:12:21,114 --> 01:12:21,974
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, that sounds great.

